06840nam a22006855i 9780822393078DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20112011ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223930787 a10.1515/97808223930782doi  a(DE-B1597)554679  a(OCoLC)728124557  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aSCI0260002bisacsh04a333.72095922200aBeyond the Sacred Forest :bComplicating Conservation in Southeast Asia /ced. by Percy E. Sajise, Michael R. Dove, Amity A. Doolittle, Arturo Escobar, Dianne Rocheleau. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (392 p.) :b7 tables, 10 maps, 11 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Ecologies for the Twenty-First Century : 4200tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAbout the Series -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tINTRODUCTION Changing Ways of Thinking about the Relations between Society and Environment -- tSECTION I. THE BOUNDARY BETWEEN NATURAL AND SOCIAL REPRODUCTION -- tOne The Wild and the Tame in Protected-Areas Management in Peninsular Malaysia -- tTwo The Implications of Plantation Agriculture for Biodiversity in Peninsular Malaysia: A Historical Analysis -- tThree Rubber Kills the Land and Saves the Community: An Undisciplined Commodity -- tSECTION II. COMMUNITY RIGHTS DISCOURSES THROUGH TIME -- tFour Adat Argument and Discursive Power: Land Tenure Struggles in Krui, Indonesia -- tFive Redefining Native Customary Law: Struggles over Property Rights between Native Peoples and Colonial Rulers in Sabah, Malaysia, 1950–1996 -- tSix The Social Life of Boundaries: Competing Territorial Claims and Conservation Planning in the Danau Sentarum Wildlife Reserve, West Kalimantan, Indonesia -- tSeven Interpreting ‘‘Indigenous Peoples and Sustainable Resource Use’’: The Case of the T’Boli in the Southern Philippines -- tSECTION III. RECONSTRUCTING AND REPRESENTING INDIGENOUS ENVIRONMENTAL KNOWLEDGE -- tEight The Historical Demography of Resource Use in a Swidden Community in West Kalimantan -- tNine The Ecological Implications of Central versus Local Governance: The Contest over Integrated Pest Management in Indonesia -- tBibliography -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aReflecting new thinking about conservation in Southeast Asia, Beyond the Sacred Forest is the product of a unique, decade-long, interdisciplinary collaboration involving research in Indonesia, Malaysia, and the Philippines. Scholars from these countries and the United States rethink the translation of environmental concepts between East and West, particularly ideas of nature and culture; the meaning of conservation; and the ways that conservation policy is applied and transformed in the everyday landscapes of Southeast Asia. The contributors focus more on folk, community, and vernacular conservation discourses than on those of formal institutions and the state. They reject the notion that conservation only takes place in bounded, static, otherworldly spaces such as protected areas or sacred forests. Thick with ethnographic detail, their essays move beyond the forest to agriculture and other land uses, leave behind orthodox notions of the sacred, discard outdated ideas of environmental harmony and stasis, and reject views of the environment that seek to avoid or escape politics. Natural-resource managers and policymakers who work with this more complicated vision of nature and culture are likely to enjoy more enduring success than those who simply seek to remove the influence and impact of humans from conserved landscapes. As many of the essays suggest, this requires the ability to manage contradictions, to relinquish orthodox ideas of what conservation looks like, and to practice continuously adaptive management techniques.Contributors. Upik Djalins, Amity A. Doolittle, Michael R. Dove, Levita Duhaylungsod